Then, if excess pCD-1 was added, a small of the amorphous FePO4 may be generated, whereas added less amount of pCD-1 could result in the insufficient phosphoric acid groups for ferric ion to form the desired product. Additionally, upon the addition of the excess of Fe3+ in reactant, the U(VI) adsorption capacity of FeyPz was distinctly decreased which can be owing to the existence of the Fe2+ reduction mechanism during the adsorption process. And the amino molecular in the reactant has no influence on the structure and adsorption property of FeyPz. However, the undried pCD-2 (EA = 0 mL) was pale yellow which indicated that the pCD was not suffered from enough condensation polymerization reaction and the as-prepared FeyPz-6 was nonuniform by naked eye (
                           Fig. S1
                        ). For the preparation of pCD, it was observed that the prepared pCD are liquid state, and then change to be viscous, and change again to be solid just like dry bitumen by increased the amount of EA from 0 to 1 mL (
                           Fig. S2
                        ). On the contrary, the state was changed from solid to be viscous after increasing the P amount in the reactant (
                           Fig. S2
                        ).

The FT-IR spectrum was acquired to verify the functional groups in pCD-6 (
                              Fig. S5
                           ). For pCD-6, the absorption peaks located at 3368, 1697, 1406, 1223, 1139 and 972 cm−1 can be attributed to the O–H/N–H stretching vibration, the C = O stretching vibration, the C–H stretching vibration, the P = O stretching vibration, the P-O-C stretching vibration [30] and the P-OH stretching vibration [5,31], respectively. The results showed that the pCD-6 contain carboxyl, hydroxyl, amine and phosphoric groups, implying that it may has good dispersion and stability in polar solvent, such as water.

The magnetic properties of Fe3O4 and FeyPz-10 are represented by the plots of magnetization (M) against the magnetic field (H), giving a hysteresis loops curve (Fig. 7
                           ). Due to the well-known ferromagnetic property of Fe3O4 
                           [28], the as-prepared Fe3O4 sample also showed magnetic stimulation response. The saturation magnetization (Ms), remanent magnetization, and coercivity of the Fe3O4 was 57.6 emu g−1, 1.1 emu g−1 and 12.6 Oe, respectively, showing that Fe3O4 is superparamagnetic but FeyPz-10 is non-magnetic. The results further verify that FeyPz-10 was not compose of Fe3O4 and Fe3O4 cannot be maintained under the condition of the addition of pCD-6 in the preparation process unless more NaOH was added.
